So the `lint()` method in wasm (used by chrome extension) calls `self.lint_group.lint()` which returns a flat `Vec<Lint>`, and then `remove_overlaps` is called.

Looking at `LintGroup::lint()`:
```rust
fn lint(&mut self, document: &Document) -> Vec<Lint> {
    self.organized_lints(document)
        .into_values()
        .flatten()
        .collect()
}
```

It flattens the BTreeMap into a Vec. The BTreeMap is ordered by key alphabetically. So `SpellCheck` lints come before `SplitWords` lints in the flat vector. Then `remove_overlaps` is called.

Let me re-examine `remove_overlaps`:

```rust
pub fn remove_overlaps(lints: &mut Vec<Lint>) {
    if lints.len() < 2 {
        return;
    }
    let mut remove_indices = VecDeque::new();
    lints.sort_by_key(|l| l.priority);
    lints.sort_by_key(|l| (l.span.start, !0 - l.span.end));
    let mut cur = 0;
    ...
}
```

So lints are sorted by priority (ascending: 31 first, 63 second), then stably sorted by `(start, end-rev)`. For the same span, the stable sort preserves the priority ordering. SplitWords (31) comes first and sets `cur = span.end`. SpellCheck (63) comes second and gets `span.start < cur`, so it's REMOVED.

So SplitWords SURVIVES and SpellCheck is REMOVED from the flat vector! That means my earlier hypothesis about priority being the issue is WRONG in the other direction - SplitWords actually has lower priority, so it survives the overlap removal.

But the bug report says SplitWords doesn't engage! This is confusing. Let me try to actually use the CLI to reproduce.

